                        <div id="content" class="hfeed">
                            <article class="post-147257 post type-post status-publish hentry category-private-lives tag-families-and-family-life des-families-and-family-life" id="post-147257">
                                <header class="postHeader">
                                    <div class="postKicker">
                                        <span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/?module=BlogCategory&amp;version=Blog Post&amp;action=Click&amp;contentCollection=Opinion&amp;pgtype=Blogs&amp;region=Header">Private Lives</a></span>
                                    </div>
                                    <h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">My Other Self</h1>
                                    <div class="story-meta-footer">
                                        <address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By James Carlos Blake			</address>
                                        <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2013-07-25T00:00:28+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">July 24, 2013 8:00 pm</time>
                                        <!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">July 24, 2013 8:00 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
                                    </div>
                                </header>
                                <div class="entry-content">
                                    <div class="inlineModule">
                                        <div class="entry">
                                            <div class="thumb"><img alt="Private Lives" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/firstperson/firstperson45.png" width="50" height="50"></div>
                                            <p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/private-lives/">Private Lives:</a> Personal essays on the news of the world and the news of our lives.
                                            </p>
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I was 6 years old when I first heard I had a twin brother. My family &#x2014; my father, my mother and I &#x2014; had recently crossed the border from Mexico to settle in Brownsville, Tex. My maternal grandmother, Mam&#xE1;
                                        Concha, lived there, too, in a little house of her own. I was always left in her care when my parents went out for a late night. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Before she was widowed and moved to Brownsville, Mam&#xE1; Concha had spent her life on isolated Mexican ranches, and she had an endless assortment of ranch stories with which to entertain me. She told of common calamities,
                                        of children drowned in wells, wranglers trampled by spooked horses, entire families perished in earthquakes, in house fires. She told of bloody murders inspired by family feuds, jealousies, injuries to honor, drunken
                                        fiestas, and she told wonderful ghost stories of every sort. I was enrapt by her stories, thrilled by them. But she said my mother would be upset if she knew I was hearing such tales, and she made me promise to
                                        keep them our secret. <span id="more-147257"></span></p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">She sometimes told me, too, of her own childhood escapades. Of spying on vaqueros bathing naked in a water tank. Of getting drunk with a friend on a pilfered half bottle of wine. Of showing her bare butt to a boy on
                                        a dare and then slapping him silly when he tried to pat it. My God, she once said, I was so bad! These stories made me laugh, but she said she would be embarrassed if my mother heard them, and she made me keep them
                                        a secret, too. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Then one night she told me of my twin. She&#x2019;d been elated when my mother telephoned from Tampico with the news of our birth, but only a few weeks later she received a call from my father informing her of my brother&#x2019;s
                                        death. A maid had been carrying him to our crib when he slipped from her arms and broke his skull on the tile floor. Mam&#xE1; Concha said my mother had nearly gone crazy with grief, and she had never since spoken
                                        of my twin. You must never mention him to your mother, Mam&#xE1; Concha said. I swore to her I would not. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But at the supper table a few nights later, I did. When I told my parents that Mam&#xE1; Concha said I had a twin, my mother stared at me a moment, then said it wasn&#x2019;t true and left the room in tears. I was shocked.
                                        My father took me in his arms and said not to worry, my mother was upset only because Mam&#xE1; Concha had told me such a thing. My grandmother was old and sick, he said, and mixed up in her mind. I mustn&#x2019;t
                                        believe the things she told me. And because he was my father, I believed him. </p>
                                    <div class="w427">
                                        <figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/07/25/pageoneplus/25privatelives-img/25privatelives-img-blog427.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span>
                                            <div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/07/25/pageoneplus/25privatelives-img/25privatelives-img-blog427.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2013/07/25/pageoneplus/25privatelives-img/25privatelives-img-blog427.jpg"
                                                    id="100000002354391" width="427" height="429" alt="">
                                                <meta itemprop="height" content="429">
                                                <meta itemprop="width" content="427">
                                            </div>
                                            <figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Aidan Koch</span>
                                            </figcaption>
                                        </figure>
                                    </div>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">They didn&#x2019;t leave me in her care anymore when they went out for an evening. They said she was too sick to look after me. I saw her only a few more times, when the three of us made brief visits to her house. On
                                        Christmas Day she was in the hospital. A few days later, she died. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The years passed. My parents had three more children. I grew up fascinated by twins and knew two sets of them in high school, and I would sometimes recall Mam&#xE1; Concha&#x2019;s troubling story. But over time I recalled
                                        it less often. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I enlisted in the army, went to college, went to work. Married and got unmarried more than once. But although I did not lack for pals or girlfriends, though my parents and I remained close, though I played sports and
                                        partied with as much zeal as the next guy, something persistently felt amiss. I lived with an almost chronic loneliness that had nothing to do with lack of company or of love. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It wasn&#x2019;t the existential angst I&#x2019;d learned about in humanities courses. It wasn&#x2019;t clinical depression. It wasn&#x2019;t just the blues. It was a confusing sense that I was somehow &#x201C;incomplete,&#x201D;
                                        something I couldn&#x2019;t explain to myself, never mind to anyone else. Strangely, the feeling was less pronounced in times of solitude. Whenever I kept my own company. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">About 15 years ago, I was living in Miami and my parents were in Central Florida when my father was given a diagnosis of cancer. He was then in his mid-80s. The doctors were not optimistic, and it seemed certain he
                                        was about to die. But he didn&#x2019;t, and he was soon back on the golf course. A year later, during one of my visits, he and I were taking a walk when he said he had a confession to make. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He had fathered a son by another woman not long before he married my mother. He told her of him, and after they wed they tried to gain custody of the child, but failed. My father never knew what became of my half brother,
                                        but he and my mother had agreed it was best to keep him a secret from me. However, after years of searching, that son had tracked him down. They had spoken on the phone, and he was coming to visit. My father was
                                        telling me all this only because there was no way to keep the secret any longer. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I told him he&#x2019;d been silly to think I&#x2019;d lose my respect for him. What did trouble me was that I had grown up believing I was his firstborn, and the realization that, had he died the year before, as he
                                        nearly did, I would never have known the truth. At which point, for the first time in years, I thought of Mam&#xE1; Concha&#x2019;s story of my twin. I reminded him of it, and asked if it was really just a senile
                                        fantasy of my grandmother&#x2019;s, or if it was true. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#x201C;Jesus Christ,&#x201D; he said, &#x201C;you remember that?&#x201D; He looked more miserable than I&#x2019;d ever seen him. And he said it was true. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It was all as Mam&#xE1; Concha had told me. Yes, my father said, my brother died when he slipped from a maid&#x2019;s arms onto a tile floor. Yes, my mother almost went mad. No, she had not spoken of him since, nor
                                        had my father ever spoken to her of him. I promised him I would not mention the matter to anyone while she lived. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He told me my brother was three minutes my elder, and that we were indistinguishable from each other. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">His name was Juan Cano Blake. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">My parents are now dead, and for reasons irrelevant to all this, I am not close to my half brother or to the siblings who were born after me. But my twin is another matter. When I learned the truth about him, I at last
                                        understood the peculiar loneliness, the persistent feeling of some indefinable lack, that I&#x2019;d lived with all my life. Juan Cano was my other self as only a twin can be, and for all those years, I had been
                                        missing him in my soul without knowing it. </p>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I&#x2019;ve now known it for a long time. And I miss him more than ever.</p>
                                    <hr>
                                    <p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><a href="//www.harpercollins.com/authors/15763/James_Carlos_Blake/index.aspx">James Carlos Blake</a> is the author, most recently, of the novel &#x201C;The Rules of Wolfe: A Border Noir.&#x201D;</em> </p>
                                </div>
                                <footer class="entry-footer">
